    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-30T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="706"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d706">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/10896: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-30T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 30, 1937—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 30—7:28 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>868. Department’s 325, October 29, 1 p.m. German Ambassador has just returned
                    from Shanghai where he went to meet wife and escort her to Nanking. He informs
                    me that he saw Kawagoe and also Ito<note n="83" xml:id="d706fn83">Nobuni Ito,
                        Japanese Minister to Poland until 1937.</note> while there, the latter at an
                    informal tea tendered him and his wife by member of Japanese Embassy. He states
                    that he received no impression that Japanese had formulated any terms, that they
                    merely talked usual generalities. I do not believe that he is acting in capacity
                    described; he seemed very pessimistic. I have just returned from a conversation
                    with Kung<note n="84" xml:id="d706fn84">H. H. Kung, Chinese Minister of Finance
                        and Vice President of the Executive Yuan (Vice Premier).</note> who in reply
                    to a question about rumors regarding peace overtures stated that Chinese would
                    not discuss peace terms with Japanese prior to Brussels Conference to which
                    Japanese case has been referred.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
